Background¶

Buying and selling used smartphones used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished phone market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth $52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used smartphones that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing a smartphone. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used smartphone market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished smartphones. Maximizing the longevity of mobile phones through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost the cheaper refurbished smartphone segment, as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished smartphones. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Dictionary¶

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the phone runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the phone battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the phone in grams
  • release_year: Year when the phone model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished phone has been used
  • new_price: Price of a new phone of the same model in euros
  • used_price: Price of the used/refurbished phone in euros

# Create a class that adds a percentage on top of each variable for each countplot inserted.
def countPct(countPlot, seriesSum):
    total = len(seriesSum)  # Number of values in each series
    for column in ax.patches:
        """ax is short for axes, which are elements of a figure, or in this context subplots of a figure.
        A figure can contain multiple axes, but for our categorial variables we just have 1 ax which is the
        count plot. .patches is a class we can use to modify the axes space, in this case adding a percentage
        to the top of each variable column.
        """
        percentage = "{:.1f}%".format(
            100 * column.get_height() / total
        )  # .1f=1 decimal float.
        x = (
            column.get_x() + column.get_width() / 2 - 0.3
        )  # Assigning x and y as the grid location of the percentage element.
        y = column.get_y() + column.get_height()
        ax.annotate(
            percentage, (x, y)
        )  # final attribute to place each percentage at the defined location.

"""Create a function stacking a histogram and boxplots together 
so that central tendency and dispersion can be visualized."""


def histogramBoxplot(series):
    # Creating a variable figure, which contains a defined number of axes, in this case 2 subplots
    figure, (axBox, axHist) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
    )
    # Number of rows of the subplot grid=2
    # Share x axis label on all subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        series, ax=axBox, showmeans=True
    )  # showmeans visualizes mean of series.
    sns.distplot(
        series, ax=axHist, kde=False
    )  # kde=False turn kernal density estimate off,
    # Create two lines on histogram that show median and mean of series, matching color of boxplot.
    axHist.axvline(np.median(series), color="black")
    axHist.axvline(np.mean(series), color="green")

Outlier Treatment¶

In [32]:
# Treat outliers in the data by flooring and capping.
def treat_outliers(df, col):
    """
    treats outliers in a variable
    col: str, name of the numerical variable
    df: dataframe
    col: name of the column
    """
    Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)  # 25th quantile
    Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)  # 75th quantile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    Lower_Whisker = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    Upper_Whisker = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # all the values smaller than Lower_Whisker will be assigned the value of Lower_Whisker
    # all the values greater than Upper_Whisker will be assigned the value of Upper_Whisker
    df[col] = np.clip(df[col], Lower_Whisker, Upper_Whisker)

    return df


def treat_outliers_all(df, col_list):
    """
    treat outlier in all numerical variables
    col_list: list of numerical variables
    df: data frame
    """
    for c in col_list:
        df = treat_outliers(df, c)

    return df

  • $R^2$=Coefficient of Determination
  • $SSR$=Sum of squared due to regression
  • $SSE$=Sum of squared errors
  • $SST$=Sum of squared total
  • $SST=SSE+SSR$
  • $R^2=\frac{SSR}{SST}$
In [40]:
def r_squared(model, X, y):
    y_mean = y.mean()
    SST = ((y - y_mean) ** 2).sum()
    SSE = ((y - model.predict(X)) ** 2).sum()
    r_square = 1 - SSE / SST
    return SSE, SST, r_square


SSE, SST, r_square = r_squared(regression_model, X_train, y_train)
print("SSE: ", SSE)

  • Adjusted $R^2$ accounts for dimensionality (the number of predictor variables) and adjusts $R^2$ respectively.
  • Adjusted $R^2$ is very close to $R^2$ indicating the high number of brand names did not effect $R^2$ too much.
  • Constant coef=Y-intercept.
  • This means if all the predictor variable coefficents are zero, the expected output (i.e., Y) would be equal to the constant coefficient. This value cannot be interpreted all the time.
  • coef of predictor variables represents change in output Y due to a change in predictor variable (everything else held constant).
  • std err reflects the level of accuracy of the coefficients.
  • lower=higher level of accuracy.

  • P>|t|=p-value.

  • For each predictor variable, there is a null hypothesis and an alternate hypothesis. Here βi is the coefficient of the ith independent variable.

  • $H_0$ : predictor variable is not significant (βi=0)

  • $H_A$ : predictor variable is significant (βi≠0)
  • P-value for each predictor variable used to check that null hypothesis.

  • 0.05 (5%) is the significance level.

  • Confidence Interval represents the range in which coefficients are likely to fall (with a likelihood of 95%).

Test for Multicollinearity¶

  • Multicollinearity is when predictor variables in a regression model are correlated, which indicates they are not independent.

  • Variance Inflation Factor (VIF): Measures inflation in the variances of the regression parameter estimates due to collinearities that exist among the predictor variables.

  • It is a measure of how much the variance of the estimated regression coefficient βk is "inflated" by the existence of correlation among the predictor variables in the model.

  • If VIF is 1, then there is no correlation among the kth predictor and the remaining predictor variables, and hence, the variance of βk is not inflated at all.

  • General Rule of thumb:

  • If VIF is between 1 and 5, then there is low multicollinearity.

  • If VIF is between 5 and 10, we say there is moderate multicollinearity.
  • If VIF is exceeding 10, it shows signs of high multicollinearity.
In [42]:
from statsmodels.stats.outliers_influence import variance_inflation_factor

# Define a function to check VIF
def checking_vif(predictors):
    vif = pd.DataFrame()
    vif["feature"] = predictors.columns

    # Calculating VIF for each feature
    vif["VIF"] = [
        variance_inflation_factor(predictors.values, i)
        for i in range(len(predictors.columns))
    ]
    return vif

Test for Linearity and Independence¶

  • Predictor variables must have a linear relation with the target variable.
  • The independence of residuals need to be confirmed, otherwise confidence intervals of the coefficient estimates will be narrower and incorrectly conclude a predictor variable to be statistically significant.
  • Linearity and independence checked with plot of fitted values vs residuals.
  • No pattern=linear and residuals are independent.
  • Otherwise, plot shows signs of non-linearity and residuals are not independent.
In [54]:
# Create a dataframe with actual, fitted and residual values

df_pred["Actual Values"] = y_train  # actual values
df_pred["Fitted Values"] = olsmod5.fittedvalues  # predicted values
df_pred["Residuals"] = olsmod5.resid  # residuals
df_pred.dropna(inplace=True)

Test for Normality¶

  • Residuals should be normally distributed.
  • If not, confidence intervals of the coefficient estimates may become too wide or narrow.

  • Once confidence interval becomes unstable, it leads to difficulty in estimating coefficients based on minimization of least squares.

  • The shape of the histogram of residuals can give an initial idea about the normality.

  • It can also be checked via a Q-Q plot of residuals.
  • If the residuals follow a normal distribution, they will make a straight line plot, otherwise not.
  • Other tests to check for normality includes the Shapiro-Wilk test.
  • Null hypothesis: Residuals are normally distributed
  • Alternate hypothesis: Residuals are not normally distributed
In [56]:
sns.histplot(data=df_pred, x="Residuals", kde=True)
plt.title("Normality of residuals")
plt.show()

Residuals have a bell shaped curve.

In [57]:
# Q-Q plot
import pylab
import scipy.stats as stats

stats.probplot(df_pred["Residuals"], dist="norm", plot=pylab)
plt.show()

Q-Q plot approximately follows a straight line, indicating normal distribution.

In [58]:
stats.shapiro(df_pred["Residuals"])
Out[58]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.8486031293869019, pvalue=8.874747154774018e-38)

Rejecting the shapiro null hypothesis technically means the residuals do not follow normal distribution, but using them as an approximation, our assumption can be satisfied.

Test for Homoscedasticity¶

  • Homoscedascity: If the variance of the residuals is symmetrically distributed across the regression line, then the data is said to be homoscedastic, otherwise it is heteroscedascity.

  • The presence of non-constant variance in the error terms results in heteroscedasticity. Generally, non-constant variance arises in presence of outliers.

  • The goldfeldquandt test can also be used. If we get a p-value > 0.05 we can say that the residuals are homoscedastic. Otherwise, they are heteroscedastic.

  • Null hypothesis: Residuals are homoscedastic
  • Alternate hypothesis: Residuals have heteroscedasticity
In [59]:
# With outliers removed, residual vs fitted values plot holds no discernable pattern.
# Goldfeldquant will be used to confirm homoscedasticity.
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
from statsmodels.compat import lzip

name = ["F statistic", "p-value"]
test = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(df_pred["Residuals"], X_train5.sample(1727))
lzip(name, test)
Out[59]:
[('F statistic', 0.6025390330386655), ('p-value', 0.9999999999998856)]

Null hypothesis holds true, residuals are homoscedastic.

  • An increase in screen size and/or weight of a phone decreases used phone price.
  • Negative coefficient for main camera megapixels indicate they're not an important feature in higher used phone pricing.
  • Internal memory and even more so RAM have high impact on used phone price.
  • Release year and days used have positive/negative coefficients respectively which make sense as newer/less used phones will price higher.
  • Apple used prices are over 172 euros higher than comparable brands in the sample.
  • Gionee, Oppo, Realme, and Vivo used phones priced ~10-14 euros lower than comparable brands in the sample.
  • Used phones with iOS operating systems priced ~206 euros lower than other operating systems in sample.
  • 4g used phones priced ~8 euros lower than non 4g used phones, while 5g used phones priced ~53 euros higher than non 5g used phones.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • Screen size, weight, and battery are highly correlated, as phone mass increases to accomodate each of these features. Screen size and weight decrease used phone price as the phone become too cumbersome to use as handheld devices.
  • Main camera megapixels become less important in higher used phone pricing, while most selfie phone megapixels are at least 15 in >8 MP models. This would indicate higher selfie camera MP should be a focused feature of high end used phone reselling.
  • Most phone models carry at least 4GB of RAM and increases in RAM size increase used phone price. This indicates 4GB RAM is the minimum needed for a fully functioning phone, with larger RAM sizes beneficial for higher end phones (such as for gaming).
  • Apple phones can sell at a higher price point in their market share, but iOS phones price lower than competing operating systems such as Android makes up over 90% of the used phone market.
  • Gionee, Oppo, Realme, and Vivo are all Chinese cellphone manufacturers that compete in a large domestic market with international brands like Huawai. Decrease in profit margin on resale value can be reflective of intense competition in these markets.
  • With 5G networks steadily growing globally, having access to 5G phones is reflected in used phone pricing, especially in proportion to the decrease of 4g phone resale price.
